 THERMAL REGION                                                   2722 1451
                                                                  2722 1451
 Evaluation May 14, 2011 by S.F Mughabghab and B. Pritychenko,BNL 2722 1451
                                                                  2722 1451
 The only available neutronic information for Co-58 is            2722 1451
 the thermal neutron capture cross section and the capture        2722 1451
 resonance integral [Mu06]. Since the (n,p) threshold is 3.090 MeV2722 1451
 below the neutron separation energy of the compound nucleus      2722 1451
 Co-59,a knowledge of the thermal (n,p) cross section is required.2722 1451
                                                                  2722 1451
  To obtain this information, two methods were applied.           2722 1451
                                                                  2722 1451
  1. The reciprocity theorem and detailed balance were applied    2722 1451
     to the reaction Fe58(p,n)Co58.                               2722 1451
     The (n,p) values thus obtained in the low keV region         2722 1451
     were extrapolated to the thermal energy by the 1/v law.      2722 1451
                                                                  2722 1451
  2. The ratio of the (n,p) cross section of Co-58 to that of     2722 1451
     Ni-59  in the kev region is determined by the EMPIRE code    2722 1451
     and then normalized to the thermal (n,p) cross section of    2722 1451
     Ni59.                                                        2722 1451
                                                                  2722 1451
    In spite of the crude assumtions, both methods, surprisingly, 2722 1451
    yielded the same thermal (n,p) cross section, 101 b for       2722 1451
    Co-58. This value is in disagreement with previous            2722 1451
    evaluations giving cross sections over 1700 b.                2722 1451
                                                                  2722 1451
